         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nKnowing the right time to plant and harvest—that is, practicing agriculture—has been part of human life for at least 10,000 years, directly influencing who we are today (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nOne of the first steps in this process was identifying the length of a year, which in this text we will consider as 365 days, rather than the actual 365 days and 6 hours it truly has (<htcite2>). However, working with such large numbers introduces inaccuracies—which is why we break them down into smaller intervals, such as seasons and weeks.\n\nBefore proceeding, let’s reflect once more on these divisions:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6f1314e-d867-4e20-9934-1b37360b562e",
                     "text": "Marlowe, F. W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2005",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a509cc9b-fbf4-43f1-be9d-9fc3faf0d1da",
                     "text": "Marlowe, F. W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1995",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "74430d2a-89e1-487d-bc92-fa19b0586ded",
                     "text": "The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica",
                     "page": "Year",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "1",
                        "day": "26"
                     }
