               "text": "#### Rise and Decline\n\nThe Amorites dominated the history of Mesopotamia, Syria, and Palestine during the second millennium BCE. Babylonian kings of this period, such as Hammurabi, belonged to this people (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nBetween <htdate0> and <htdate1>, there are no records of the Amorite language being used in the region, although this did not imply the disappearance of their civilization.\n\nGroups referred to as \"Amorites\" reappeared, causing conflicts with the Neo-Assyrian Empire, and there is evidence that they influenced other peoples, such as the Hebrews (<htcite2>; <htcite3>).\n\n#### Hammurabi\n\nA dedicated text on Hammurabi will be published in the *Genealogical Trees* section, but it is worth mentioning his famous code of laws, written around <htdate2>, a copy of which is preserved in the British Museum (Figure 2). This code presents notable similarities to Jewish texts written more than a millennium later (<htcite4>; <htcite5>).",
